explanation:
Automatic terminal information service (ATIS)
. The automatic provision of current, routine information to arriving and departing aircraft throughout 24 hours or a specified portion thereof:
Data link-automatic terminal information service
(D-ATIS). The provision of ATIS via data link.
Voice-automatic terminal information service
(Voice-ATIS). The provision of ATIS by means of continuous and repetitive voice broadcasts.
In general, it contains information that is provided by MET and SPECIAL reports as well as operational information such as the name of the aerodrome etc. The information is as follows:
General information such as the name of the aerodrome;
Time of observation;
Type of the expected approach;
State of the runway;
Direction (referenced to magnetic north) and speed of surface wind
;
Horizontal visibility and runway visual range
;
Present weather phenomena;
Clouds
;
Air temperature and dew point;
Altimeter setting;
Other information that is relevant for flight.

ICAO Annex 3
SIGMET information
.
Information issued by a meteorological watch office concerning the occurrence or expected occurrence of specified en-route weather phenomena which may affect the safety of aircraft operations.
According to ICAO Annex 3, a SIGMET will be issued for:
thunderstorm;
heavy hail;
tropical cyclone;
freezing rain;
severe turbulence (not associated with convective cloud);
severe icing (not associated with convective cloud);
severe mountain waves;
heavy sand/dust storm;
volcanic ash cloud.
In this case, the SIGMET is issued in reference to severe Clear Air Turbulence, which is
not within a cloud
, and can therefore
not be detected by any RADAR or weather satellite
as they only pick up clouds and precipitation, nor can it be accurately modelled in most cases. This SIGMET is most likely to have come from
pilot reports
in the area.

